Decision and rationale:
I choose the Polished late‑period pop‑rock album because, overall, it aligns more closely with the concrete technical and musical priorities I listed: tactile analogue piano/synth with restored transient detail, a remaster that preserves headroom and microdynamics, intimate close‑miked midrange vocals, concise hook songs, and cohesive single‑period sequencing. Those attributes directly support the things I value most—piano forward mixes, preserved dynamics, intimacy and LP‑style flow—while the description indicates restraint in the mastering (no loudness chase) and attention to transient/piano detail.
I reject Turn It On Again: The Hits because it is a hits compilation with a groove/rhythm‑first presentation, locked bass/drums and tight low‑end emphasis, plus warm baritone lead and stacked backing. Those qualities run counter to my preference for piano‑forward, sparsely arranged, close‑vocal, early‑70s analogue‑mids aesthetics and my dislike of compilation-style sequencing and groove/low‑end dominance that can obscure tactile piano and conversational lead vocal nuance.

